<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Application Setup on Backslash PHP Developer Guide</title><link>https://backslashphp.github.io/backslash/application-setup/</link><description>Recent content in Application Setup on Backslash PHP Developer Guide</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-ca</language><atom:link href="https://backslashphp.github.io/backslash/application-setup/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Defining Services</title><link>https://backslashphp.github.io/backslash/application-setup/defining-services/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://backslashphp.github.io/backslash/application-setup/defining-services/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="defining-services"&gt;Defining Services&lt;a class="anchor" href="#defining-services"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using a dependency injection container is beneficial for bootstrapping Backslash applications. The number of components
and their dependencies makes a container practical for managing instantiation and wiring.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The demo application implements its own PSR-11 container in &lt;code&gt;src/Infrastructure/Container.php&lt;/code&gt; for demonstration
purposes. In production applications, prefer using your framework&amp;rsquo;s built-in container (Laravel, Symfony, Slim, etc.) or
a dedicated container library like &lt;code&gt;php-di/php-di&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;league/container&lt;/code&gt;. These mature containers provide features like
auto-wiring, configuration caching, and better performance.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Registering Handlers</title><link>https://backslashphp.github.io/backslash/application-setup/registering-handlers/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://backslashphp.github.io/backslash/application-setup/registering-handlers/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="registering-handlers"&gt;Registering Handlers&lt;a class="anchor" href="#registering-handlers"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The boot process registers commands with the dispatcher and events with the event bus, establishing the routing between
messages and their handlers. This registration happens after service definitions are loaded but before the application
handles any requests or executes commands.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="understanding-the-boot-process"&gt;Understanding the boot process&lt;a class="anchor" href="#understanding-the-boot-process"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The boot process consists of:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Registering commands&lt;/strong&gt; with command handlers in the dispatcher&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Registering events&lt;/strong&gt; with projectors in the event bus&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Registering events&lt;/strong&gt; with processors in the event bus (skipped during projection rebuilds)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This registration should happen once during application startup.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Using the Bootstrap File</title><link>https://backslashphp.github.io/backslash/application-setup/using-the-bootstrap-file/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://backslashphp.github.io/backslash/application-setup/using-the-bootstrap-file/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="using-the-bootstrap-file"&gt;Using the Bootstrap File&lt;a class="anchor" href="#using-the-bootstrap-file"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
